	that
	<i>the
	</i>marks
	agents
	and</p>
	<p>
	ACQUISITION	153</p>
	<p>
	<br/>

	</p>
	<p>
	<i>a
	</i>marks
	patients.
	Since
	<i>the
	</i>often
	co-occurs
	with
	NPs
	that
	are
	physically
	present
	and
	<i>a
	</i>with
	NPs
	that
	are
	physically
	absent
	one
	might
	hy&shy;
	pothesize
	that
	<i>the
	</i>and
	<i>a
	</i>mark
	poles
	of
	some
	kind
	of
	proximal-distal
	distinction.
	In
	fact,
	so
	far
	as
	we
	know,
	such
	hypotheses
	are
	never
	made.
	In
	any
	case,
	they
	would
	affect
	only
	<i>a
	</i>and
	<i>the;
	</i>with
	regard
	to
	<i>a
	</i>alone,
	why
	on
	earth
	should
	
	the
	
	child
	even
	start
	by
	hypothesizing
	
	that
	 there
	are
	really
	two
	
	kinds
	
	of
	<i>a?
	
	</i>Moreover,
	
	since
	two-year-olds
	
	use
	
	few
	or
	no
