	shall show
	that some puzzling
	features of
	those studies
	become immediately
	 clear 
	once  we  assume
	that while
	the subjects
	of these
	studies appear
	to be
	merely learning
	French and
	Italian, respectively,
	the  bioprogram 
	decisively  influences
	the progress
	of their
	acquisition.</p>
	<p>
	One point
	must be
	made fu:st,
	however. With
	few exceptions,
	students of
	acquisition assume
	that when
	a child
	uses a
	past-tense form, he
	uses it
	because he
	fully understands,
	and deliberately
	intends <i>t
	</i>mark,
	pastness of
	reference.<sup>5</sup><sup>
	</sup>True, it
	is often
