	5	<sub>8	</sub><sup>P-1</sup>
		<p align="left" style="margin-left: 0in; line-height: 0.85in">e</p>
	
	</p>
	<h1>
	8</h1>
</div>
<div id="Bereich157" dir="ltr" gutter="114" style="column-count: 2">
	<p>
	acquisition charts
	I have
	ever seen
	, this
	one does
	not show
	a consistent<sup>	6</sup></p>
	<p>
	and steadv
	rise from
	low to
	high percentages
	of correct
	forms; rather it
	shows  he
	familiar fever-chart
	zigzags before
	coming to
	rest, at
	age</p>
	<p>
	0</p>
	<p>
	Table 3.3</p>
</div>
<div id="Bereich158" dir="ltr" gutter="43" style="column-count: 2">
	<p>
	7 :8,
	with fairly
	uniform percentages
	of past
	marking across
	all action types.
	In Bronckart
	and Sinclair's
	presentation, I
	think quite
	unin&shy; tentionally,
	the amount
	of zigzagging
	is reduced
	by showing
	two different graphs
	for durative
	and nondurative
	events; thus,
	certain very
	interesting crossover
