	cookies
	</i>in
	/47/
	is
	not
	the
	same
	as
	<i>eating
	cookies
	</i>in
	/49/.
	In
	/47
	/,
	it
	expresses
	a
	particular
	
	nonpunctual
	
	action
	
	in
	
	realis
	
	time;
	in
	/49/,
	it
	expresses
	the
	abstract
	concept
	of
	an
	action,
	not
	necessarily
	either
	punctual
	or
	nonpunctual,
	in
	irrealis
	time.
	The
	superficial
	identity
	of
	the
	forms
	involved
	is
	an
	illusory
	one,
	and
	the
	child,
	for
	all
	the
	little
	he
	is
	supposed
	to
	know
	of
	language,
	is
	not
	fooled
	by
	it.
	For
	hoth
	child
	and
	creole,
	nonpunctual
	means
