	<p>
	Lamendella defends
	the  foregoing
	model  against 
	accusations of
	Larnarckism by
	pointing out
	that in
	all
	species,
	individual members
	show differences
	in  their capacities.
	Thus, at
	any given
	stage of
	the development toward
	full language,
	relatively slight
	differences in
	the associated
	capacities would
	have conferred
	a selective
	advantage on their
	possessors, so
	that there
	would have
	developed &quot;a
	concentration</p>
	<p>
	of genotypes
	producing [these
	capacities J
	in the
	gene pool
	of the species.&quot;
	Thus, the
	average capacity
	of the
	hominid line
	at stage
	n+l would 
	have  equaled 
	the  maximum 
	capacity  at 
	stage <i>n,
	</i>and 
	the  bio-</p>
	<p>
	'</p>
