		It is
		interesting to
		note that
		while ft-clauses
		in complement
		position
		can refer
		to one-time
		actions (as
		in /210/),
		and in
		consequence the
		higher verb
		can take
		punctual marking,
		preposed ft-clauses
		can refer only
		to habitual
		actions, and
		in consequence
		the higher
		verb must
		take nonpunctual
		marking. At
		the moment
		I have
		no idea
		why this
		is so.</p>
